1. He was referring to Atlantic Canada, not Western Canada. The latitude if London in eastern Canada would be considered northern. Also many computer models were accurate. Hansen et al., 1981 Predicted a rise if 0.65C from 1981 to 2017 (latest year with data presented on website). In reality 2017 was about 0.75C warmer than ~1980. 1988 Hansen et al. Predicted a rise of temps of 0.9C by 2017. Reality was 0.75C. This is because he predicted an increased use of halocarbons, which were mostly banned by the Montreal Protocol. This is why the prediction was higher. The prediction of CO2 concentrations was very similar to what was observed. IPCC 1990 first assessment Predicted a mean of 0.84C rise, when in reality is was 0.75. However this was within the margin of error. IPCC 1995 2and assessment Predicted a rise if 0.55C. In reality it was 0.75. This is means the projection actually underestimated global warming. IPCC 2001 third assessment Projected a 0.62C rise, which again underestimated the warming observed. As you can see, many projections that accounted for a rise in CO2 concentrations found that we were to expect warming, which is what we observed. https://www.carbonbrief.org/analysis-how-well-have-climate-models-projected-global-warming

We're in an interglacial period of the ice age, which means that average worldwide temperatures should start to decrease (over the next few dozen millennia). Fluctuations in average temperatures are normal, but not at the pace we're seeing now; the rapid increase in temperature is mostly, though not entirely, driven by greenhouse gas emissions. It can be difficult to grasp for those of us who haven't dedicated our careers to climatology and other climate sciences, but the cause for concern is due to the rate at which it's changing. 100 years is a long time for us, but those of us who study the natural sciences know that a century is essentially nothing in geologic terms. The entire existence of the Gulf Stream is contingent on the saltier waters not significantly mixing with the surrounding waters, due to differences in density. Otherwise, the salinity and temperature of all ocean waters would simply equalize, and the whole thing wouldn't work. So how is it that under current conditions mixing does not take place, but under conditions of melting polar ice, with a far greater salinity, and therefore density, gradient, this principle would suddenly reverse itself and the waters would mix freely, decreasing the salinity of Gulf Stream waters north of Iceland?

Kudos to Atlas Pro for distinguishing between "hypothesis" and "theory"!

"Hypothesis" is an untested idea which appears to fit known data.

'Theory" is held to a higher standard of making quantifiable and testable predictions. Known data fits. New data is collected and fits predictions made using a theory.

A theory must be altered or discarded if experimental data shows predictions made using the theory to be false.

Those who say "It's (just) a theory" acknowledge its credibility. Kinda like gravity. It's just a theory. Test it by taking a jump from the top of the Empire State Building or the tallest building accessible to you.

Or, like Galileo, let two cannonballs of different weights do the jumping for you.

So what controls and modulates the interglacial cycle? Answer - orbital cycles and ice sheet albedo.

Milankovitch orbital cycles provide the basis, but the surface feedback mechanism is albedo, not CO2. The albedo effect as measured in the high NH latitudes is orders of magnitude greater that any CO2 effects. Ice ages would continue indefinitely, if the high albedo of the ice-sheets could not be lowered.



So what lowers ice sheet albedo? Answer - dust.

You forget to take into account that you're looking at the East Coast of America. If you compare the West Coast, we see similar temperatures up to Portland and Vancouver than in Europe. Although, sure, it is on a much thinner strip. But at 3:40 you clearly show a circulation map with a cold current around the East Coast of America and a warm one on the West Coast, similar to the warm current in Europe.
Add to that the fact that Europe has 2 and a half inland seas (the Mediterranean, the Baltic and the North Sea that, although connected to the Arctic, is still continental crust meaning shallow waters ‚Äî¬†also keep in mind that's the case for the English Channel and the Irish Sea), then the warmer temperatures and, most importantly, warmer winters make sense. Water acts as a buffer since it takes much longer to cool down than land. That's why part of Russia that are at the same latitude as the UK are much much colder. Scotland, for example, is further North than Moscow. It's a lot warmer, though. Same goes for Norway. If you stick to the US, San Francisco and Sacramento are basically at the same latitude as Washington DC.


Now, would ice melting completely nullify those currents? Well, sure, there have been examples of the Gulf Stream halting to a stop and all. But salinity is not the only thing driving these currents. It's also trade winds that are linked to the Coriolis effect. And whatever you do, water to the south will be warmer, pushing it to the surface and making it expand, while colder water will sink.

To suggest that there is absolutely a consensus is either incredibly ignorant, or incredibly deceptive. I literally just finished reading an article in scientific American where they were discussing two different reputable groups of geologists that were arguing over the temperature fluctuations of the last 20 years. It is absolutely factually incorrect, borderline dishonest to suggest that there's a consensus.

He did however say there was no consensus. And he later forgot to include a crucial aspect from early on: "the westerlies" pushing warm water towards Europe. As long as the AMOC stays intact, it will keep Europe warmer. Second, he makes no mention of solar activity. The Maunder Minimum etc. are closely related to solar activity cycles, specifically the 115 year cycle. Right now we're at a minimum, yet still temperatures rise globally and now even in the Antarctic ice cap shrinks. In about 60 years there's the solar maximum. This further speeds up ice melt, and I don't think there is any telling of what effect this will have at the deep ocean current. The massive cold "unsalty" water dump can drastically slow down the deep current, but if in 60 - 70 years there isn't much Arctic ice left to melt anymore... that dump is over really fast. Third, the more Arctic ice retreats, the more the cool surrounding meltwater retraits too, that creates a northern barrier for both the westerlies and AMOC. Fourth, the past years we've seen cold air being pushed down from the Arctic, particularly in N-America. With ever more ice melting, this push weakens. Meaning warmer air farther up north. Which then ties into the end of my second point. But at this point much is still speculation. Whatever influence becomes dominant, it's going to get real unpleasant near the equator.

@lord freezer "So what," you ask? I've been a mechanical engineer for 40 years and make a living running computer simulations of structures. So I know a thing or two about the limits of what conclusions can be drawn from simulations. So yeah, I understand the reasoning. Do you? Engineers have an adage: "If you torture data long enough, it will tell you anything you want to hear." I have several beefs about how we're approaching climate change: (1) There's no accountability for the predictions because there are no metrics for the accuracy. It's one thing to predict a certain reduction in, say, the rise of the sea-level. But we're not even doing that. In the equation, CO2 is an input, not an output. Making a goal of an input is useless if there is no continuous comparison to the output. It's great to make a goal of reducing CO2, but is that reduction providing enough of the desired end effect? If it doesn't provide the desire effect, who is accountable for that failure? No one? (2) There is very little evidence that there has been any thought given to the validity of the risk assessment and the effectiveness of the risk management. Climate change is indeed a real risk. But how severe of a risk, really? Might they be fear-mongering a gullible population and making feel-good proposals to virtue-signal that doing something is better than doing nothing? Money is a limited resource. Everything has an return on investment (ROI). The equation must always begin with "How much money are we willing to spend?" and the answer is NOT "The cost doesn't matter because we must do this." For every proposal to reduce sea-level rise, I want to know up front how much money will be spent, what the ROI is predicted to be, and milestones along the way to measure whether or not it's working as predicted. And it if falls short of predictions, then you re-calculate the ROI to decide if the money isn't better spent elsewhere so that you don't throw good money after bad. And if you say that the climate is too complex to hold people accountable for the accuracy of the predictions, then what's your rationale for being so certain that we know what changes have to occur? They're not talking about running experiments to test theories. They're acting like it they are already certain of it, and there is so much money at stake they are going to be very motivated to maintain the consensus. (3) Among climatologists, there isn't even agreement over whether or not the current trends can be halted (outputs like sea-level rise, not inputs like CO2 emissions). Some say that it is already too late. If true, then there is little value to throwing money at preventing a disaster that is inevitable at some uncertain time in the future, just because the ones who want their pet programs to be funded are hawking the notion, "Doing something is better than doing nothing." That's a conflict of interest, and billions of dollars are at stake. My being skeptical of the effectiveness of the proposals is justified.

It's "The Day After Tomorrow"s plot, rehashed. Back in 2004, Roland Emmerich (the director famous for "Independence Day,") made a Climate-Change fueled sci-fi movie about Global Warming reaching such a hostile pinnacle that the "Gulf Stream," or "North Atlantic Current," lost all salinity due to rampant melting polar ice, and completely shut down. What makes this film fictional is the idea that the current shutting down caused an immediate planetary climate-holocaust that affected the entire Northern Hemisphere, and a month-long, planet-wide blizzard that covered everything down to Mexico and Africa in hundreds of feet of snow.


Now, obviously, the speed at which this event happened was entirely fictional. No Ice Age ever came about in a matter of weeks or months. It came about in YEARS, if not centuries. But the fundamental theory that shapes the film, according to this video, is absolutely plausible! If the North Atlantic Current (which powers the entire world's current-system by sheer momentum) were to break down. The ocean's natural recycling of warm water to northern climates would cease. Over time, this would cause an equalization of Earth's latitudinal temperature rules, causing hightened warming at the equator, but excessive cooling at the polar ice caps. The ice caps themselves would, over centuries, replenish their ice sheets and traditional cycles, but at the expense of the warm-temperate climate, worldwide, that enabled mankind to dominate the Earth to begin with.


As this video points out; it would happen VERY SLOWLY, (over a century's length, at the very fastest) so none of us alive now would ever live to see the final result. It might even be happening right at this moment, but since we're at the very beginning of this process, none of us can notice. To us, the Earth seems to be still warming. It'll take years, if not decades, for that momentum we are all used to seeing, to slow to a stop. Decades beyond that to move in the opposite direction. Nothing by Earth's standards moves fast. If an Ice Age of our own cause is approaching, it is not us, but our children, and most prominently our grandchildren, who will face the consequences. "The Day After Tomorrow" appears to be a not only plausible, but LIKELY, outcome of our fiddling with nature. It just won't happen at "Hollywood Speed." It'll happen at (pardon the expression) a "glacial" pace. We'll live long enough to see the beginning of the process, but none of us will ever live long enough to see the end result of it.

@epicrotfl... The Quartenary did not end 11000 years ago. It still continues. What ended 11700 years ago was a glacial period (called the Pleistocene Epoch) within the current ice age (called the Quartenary Period) . An Ice Age has glacial and interglacial periods. Glacial periods are periods of glacial expansion (rapid global cooling) Interglacial periods are periods of glacial retreat (rapid global warming.) We are currently in an interglacial, called the Holocene Epoch (that started 11700 years ago). These periods of warming and cooling are triggered by the Melankovich cycles (these include eccentricity of the Earth's orbit, tilt of the earth's axis and precession of the Earth's axis) These factors change cyclicly. Thus they produce cycles of glaciation when certain other factors are in place (eg. ocean currents...which are mostly determined by the position of continents. As well as feedback loops. Eg. exposed continental crust near polar regions covered in snow, reflecting sunlight. etc). These state of conditions currently exist...and are responsible for the presence of ice caps. Which have been there for 2.6 million years. As long as those conditions exist and ice caps are present...we're still in an Ice Age.

Remember the equation on wikipedia: (1-a)S=4 e s T^4 you can easily calculate equilibrium T from this. I'll do it for you: S = 1367; % Solar constant a = 0.3; % Earth average albedo s = 5.67e-8; % Stefan-Boltzmann constant e = 0.612; % Effective emissivity of earth T = ((1-a)*S/(4*e*s))^(1/4) - 273.15 = 15 (degree C) now if you google solar cycle, look for images, you'll see the value of S varying between 1367 and 1365 (W m-2) if I use S = 1365 I get: T = ((1-a)*S/(4*e*s))^(1/4) - 273.15 = 14.9 (degree C) As you can see... that's not a big change. The solar cycle doesn't have a big impact on Earth climate (but milankovitch cycle does!! but on much longer time scale.) In the equation, what has changed and continue to change is global albedo (a) and the effective emissivity of Earth. If e was 1 (without atmospheric CO2), we would have: e= 1; T = ((1-a)*S/(4*e*s))^(1/4) - 273.15 = -18.3 (degree C) 33 degree C colder! So it's a good thing we have some CO2 in the atmosphere. now, if the effective emissivity of Earth was 0, that would mean that all heat is trapped on earth... at 0, the temperature would just keep increasing (there is no T equilibrium, because there's only heat going in, and no heat going out - T keeps increasing). On some planet, such as Venus, there is a lot of greenhouse gas, causing T to be very high. Average temperature on Venus is 462 degree C. Good Questions! When seawater freezes, it typically freezes slowly enough that water forms crystalline structures which do not leave space for the salt molecules to remain. This is why icebergs and glaciers contain freshwater. You are right in the sense that ice already in the ocean does not contribute to rising sea levels. But the point of this video is to describe how current climate change patterns causing the melting of ice in the Artic lead to an Ice Age, causing higher temperatures near the equator and lower temperatures near the north. @Roland Deschain You shouldn't link things you don't understand. A winshield not heating up as much as a carhood does not violate thermodynamics. A windshield simply does not obstruct as much light as a carhood. Therefore, it converts less energy from light to heat than a carhood does. This is not difficult. This is not top-tier science. This is the stuff 11-year olds learn in school. Ice doesn't heat up as fast as basalt in sunlight, because ice _reflects far more sunlight than basalt._ If we create an atmosphere that does not lose heat quickly, then heat (from the sun, yes) will accumulate on the planet faster, simply because the atmosphere traps more of it. Just like a blanket doesn't warm you up; it merely traps your bodyheat. 'Climate Change' is a complicated issue; in part, it's weather changes due to deforestation and desertification, in part it's weather changes due to increased temperatures affecting the oceans. Information I've seen shows the Medieval Warm Period (MWP) to have been as warm or warmer than today. What caused the end of the MWP and the beginning of the Little Ice Age (LIA) is up for debate and the two leading contenders I've seen for what caused it to end are volcanic activity and solar activity. The coldest period of the LIA began in the 1600s, by which time solar activity was being monitored, so we know that in the 1600s solar activity decreased greatly and entered what called a Grand Solar Minimum. This grand solar minimum is referred to as the Maunder Minimum named after the scientist who was measuring daily solar activity at that time. In 1815 the eruption of Mount Tambora caused a volcanic winter which lasted for a number of years and caused the year without a summer in 1816. After the effects of the Tambora eruption subsided the earth began to warm until the 1940s when a global cooling trend began which lasted until the the late 1970s. This is why in the 1970s many scientists and some government agencies were concerned about or predicting the beginning of a new ice age. The Little Ice Age was caused by a Grand Solar Minimum called the Maunder Minimum. A weakened solar magnetic field leaves the earth more susceptible to cosmic rays penetrating our lower atmosphere. There is, indeed, no such thing as a 'pure capitalist market.' Not in a system where value is given quantifiable representation (money). However, 'capitalism' is not the same as 'pure free market.' @Stirgid Lanathiel Value is generated by labor. The simplistic, idealized model of capitalism you described doesn't exist, has never existed and never can. There's no such thing as an ideal free market or "pure capitalism", economic power is always combined with political power. In practice this means capital being used to generate more capital, surplus value being extracted from exploited labor and market speculation. @Transsylvanian I both agree and disagree with you there. The idea that capitalism requires infinite growth isn't entire true. Rather, more truth would lie, if you ask me, in the assumption that the kind of world economy we are currently enjoying is not, strictly speaking, capitalist. Capitalism occurs when two parties trade objects, and both parties consider themselves to have gained more worth than they lost. For example: A hunter trades a deer for an axe at the flinter. The flinter, who has worked to create the axe, values a deer more than the hunter, who is in need of a new axe. In this transaction, _worth_ is created in excess by the experience of value of both participants. This is the sense in which capitalism has a theoretically infinite ability to generate wealth through worth, through essentially people's _perception_ of the value of products. What is happening currently, however, is an upper class who siphons that value out of the overall economy. An example here is investment and shares. Shares were initially created so that entrepreneurs could create businesses that were too large for the entrepreneurs to afford. They did this by selling shares of the future profit to people; people would buy those shares, and in return would (eventually) get profit, while the entrepreneur would now have a vast sum of money to invest. The problem is that those who held those shares would then sell those shares to other people; the stock market. Every time a share is sold for a profit, a bit of that share's value disappears in the profit that is made. When the top % of the population makes its money by doing so (or employing people who do so on their behalf), then that lost value disappears into their bank accounts, where it effectively doesn't exist. It does not circulate back into the economy. That is why this system requires infinite value; because value is depleted infinitely (over time), rather than created. I think that itself makes a very good case that this system that is our downfall is _not_ Capitalism.

7:30 there is actually some evidence of the Gulf Stream slowing down, maybe even stopping.
There are these microscopic sea life creatures called phorams that grow shells, to grow the shells they must get nutrients, normally, when the Gulf Stream is flowing most of these nutrients pass over the phorams and so they can't grow their shells as much (the shells become thin).
But if the Gulf Stream slows down, or even stops these nutrients will flow down to the seabed, so as a result the shells of these phorams will be thick.
So by looking at how thick/thin the shells of these phorams are and when they lived we can understand when they Gulf Stream has slowed down.

Oh yeah. One more thing. As saltwater around the poles get more fresh from the melting glaciers and ice sheets, the salinity will drop, which, will result in the water being able to freeze at a higher temperature (100% pure water freezes at 0 degrees celsius, obviously). Then the ice sheets will reflect alot of the sunlight back, and they will form a solid platform where snow can sit, which will reflect even more sunlight back. That will also cool down the earth even more. And as the gulf stream is weakened from the previous cooling of water from the ice being melted, the amount of warm water being able to hit the poles is reduced a lot, which also, will cool down the poles even more, to the point where sea water with higher salinity will freeze more easy because of the lower temperatures, which will create ice and do the same exact thing as I mentioned first.


So in theory, the poles will get MUCH colder for a period, and the average temperature on high latitudes of the northern and southern hemisphere will also get colder. But the equator will heat up, because the warm water around there has nowhere to go as explained in the video, which in the end will reverse most of this (For a period).


I am located in Denmark btw, and another thing about why Europe is on average much warmer than America, is because we have sea (Island) climate, instead of continental climate (like the USA has). The sea around Europe, (Which is also warmer than that of the USA at same latitudes), will cool down the land in the summer, but heat it up in the winter. Oh yeah and the main mountain ranges here in Europe are also mostly running from west to east (Alps, pyrenees, dinarian alps, scottish highlands, and some parts of the scandinavian mountains), which will block the amount of cold air being transferred from the poles, to mainland Europe because of pressure systems building up on the north side of the mountains. That also explains why we usually get the coldest cold fronts from the east (Siberia/ Russia), and not from the Scandinavian peninsula (We also get cold fronts from there, or Denmark does atleast). Oh yeah and the average altitude in continental north Europe (North of the alps, south of the Scaninavian Peninsula) here is also a bit lower than the US.

Very few of the actual outcomes of Global Warming are in and of themselves strictly undesirable. Less rainwater means less flooding, unless you weren't afraid of that in the first place. More rainwater means cheaper water, unless it's already free because you get too much. Warmer temperatures means shorter winters, i.e. longer growing seasons. The problem is that the biosphere prefers to have a few centuries to adapt to change and we're already straining many species, many of which we already strained past what they could adapt much faster than what we generally see in the fossil record outside of extinction events. We tend to like the biosphere for the most part and don't particularly care to find out how much of it we can remove before we have to start supporting ourselves biologically. In addition, different weather patterns means that we're going to have to change our infrastructure all over the world to deal with whatever the new climates become. You start having more droughts, that means more water storage in reservoirs. More flooding, better drainage, and perhaps the need to construct large pipes that take excess water to the places with droughts. More storms, better methods of dealing with them so you don't have a refugee crisis on the coasts every storm season. All of that is expensive, and especially for poorer nations, they're just going to have to change their lifestyle to cope while richer nations like America are going to need to deal with higher costs associated with living the way we want to where we want to. Now personally, I think that some of these solutions should be undertaken even if Global Warming weren't a thing. Honestly, it's pitiful how poorly we deal with major storms that hit cities. But yea, the story of Global Warming for the most part is, we know that temperatures on average are going to rise, and we're not seeing too many positive outcomes and plenty detrimental ones, but exact effects on places are still subject to many things we are less certain about. In a way it's like the fact that we can understand how the universe is likely to end despite the fact that predicting human society past a few decades is currently impossible as there are way too many potential technologies each of which could have major effects on society.

I wasn't talking about all Brits, but Brexiters or even more particularly those people in government who felt they could get away with half-assed negotiations. Whether you like it or not: Brexiters did make arguments based on post imperial delusions of grandeur - like "The EU needs Britain (and access to its market) more than the other way around, so desperately the UK will be able to dictate terms and get all the benefits of EU membership with none of the resposibilities" or "once the UK leaves the Britain will be able to negotiate trade deals with the entire world - as though the entire world just waited for that and would make getting a trade agreement with 65 million consumer Britain their top priority..." @Merry Machiavelli The time to discuss and decide most of the issues the various factions have with the separation agreement, would have been before article 50 was triggered. It was madness to go into the negotions with no idea what the country wants to get out of the separation agreement. Decisions like soft brexit or hard brexit or how to deal with Northern Ireland, should have been made before the negotiations started. But since these issues were not settlend within the UK, they couldn't possibly be settled in the separation agreement. And when Theresa May finally defined a position (the Chequers-Plan) - one and a half years late - she lost about half her cabinet. It's as though someone went to a car-dealership to negotiate a lease with no clues whether he (or she) wants to lease a car, a lorry or a tractor. Had the UK government done this properly and defined its goal before it started the process, the UK wouldn't be in that "quagmire of indecision" now. When the negotiations started, Michel Barnier complained publically how poorly the british delegation was prepared, how little interest his the counterpart David Davis seemed to take (the man couldn't even be bothered to be present the entire time) and that the delegations leaders didn't seem to understand the consequences of their positions. Davis is a brexit hardliner and in retrospect it seems he wasn't negotiating in good faith but deliberately sabotaging the negotations to make sure there wouldn't be a successful separation agreement, thus guarantueeing a diamond hard brexit. Having someone oversee the negotiations of the separation agreement who wants to cut all ties and doesn't understand why a separation agreement is needed in the first place was a royally stupid move. Neither of those issues have anything to do with how complex the matter is. They have to do with infighting due to poor leadership and the failure to make decisions when they needed to be made. The EU has gone out of its way to protect the British people from the idiocy of their leaders. I'm not sure about Spain. British politicians are not used to compromise; most of them see compromise as a sign of weakness and failure.

That part is a circulation, though. Natural processes producing CO2 are balanced out by natural processes removing CO2 from the atmosphere, more or less. What we're doing (and have been doing for the last one and a half century) is taking a lot of carbon out of the ground and blowing it into the atmosphere as CO2, i.e. _adding_ CO2 into the circulation. So it's not the absolute percentage of CO2 that humans produce, it's that basically all of the _rise_ in the atmospheric levels of CO2 is due to human activity. This has been mitigated a bit by additional absorption of oceans and plant life but not nearly enough.

@Colin Watson The Gulf Stream is driven by the trade winds and technically starts off the west coast of Africa at the equator. It gets confined by the South American continental shelf and then the Gulf of Mexico continental shelf and then flows north. It starts with the equatorial trade winds (blowing east to west) and the rotation of the Earth. The return system starts under the sea ice in the Arctic ocean where it sinks and stays in each Arctic ocean basin for 400 years or so. Then it finally flows over the choke points out in the north Atlantic (at the very bottom bottom because it is the most dense water there is on the planet) and it flows all the way to the south Atlantic where it runs into the Antarctic bottom water and slowly surfaces somewhere in the south Atlantic. So stop the winds, stp the rotation of the Earth, stop the 180 days of darkness in the Arctic, tilt the Earth differently and you can stop the AMOC. In other words, this has not happened in 4.4 billion years.
